ed HIV vaccine{{clarify|there is no such thing as an HIV vaccine|date=January 2018}}\n* [[Y. D. Sharma]], molecular biologist<ref name=\"Indian fellow - Y D Sharma\">{{Cite web |url=http://insaindia.res.in/detail/P06-1423 |title=Indian fellow - Y D Sharma |date=2017 |publisher=Indian National Science Academy}}</ref>\n* [[Janak Raj Talwar]], cardiovascular surgeon<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{Cite web |url=http://medind.nic.in/ibq/t03/i1/ibqt03i1p82.pdf |title=Obituary |last=J. S. Guleria |date=2017 |publisher=National Databases of Indian Medical Journals}}</ref>\n* [[Shashi Wadhwa]], neuroscientist<ref name=\"Prof. Shashi Wadhwa\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.aiims.edu/aiims/emfacility/shashi-wadhwa.htm |title=Prof. Shashi Wadhwa |website=aiims.edu |access-date=2017-12-16}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n\n{{All India Institutes of Medical Sciences}}\n{{Delhi}}\n{{Universities in Delhi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:All India Institute of Medical Sciences}}\n[[Category:Hospitals in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Medical colleges in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Medical Council of India]]\n[[Category:Regional Cancer Centres in India]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1956]]\n[[Category:All India Institute of Medical Sciences, New Delhi]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in India]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Delhi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian medical school and hospital in New Delhi}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name              = All India Institute of Medical Sciences, New Delhi\n| native_name       = \n| image_name        = [[File:All India Institute of Medical Sciences, Delhi.svg|200px]]\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Official [[seal (emblem)|seal]] of AIIMS (New Delhi)\n| motto             = Shar\u012bram\u0101dyam khalu dharmas\u0101dhanam\n| mottoeng          = \"The body is indeed the primary instrument of ''[[dharma]]''.\"\n| established       = {{start date and age|1956}} \n| type              = [[Public university|Public]] [[medical school]] \n| endowment         = \n| president         = Harsh Vardhan\n| dean              = Vinay Kumar Bahl\n| director          = Randeep Guleria\n| academic_staff    = 671<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\">{{cite web|title=63rd AIIMS Annual Report 2018\u20132019|url=https://www.aiims.edu/images/pdf/annual_reports/annual%20report19-e-20-1-20.pdf|publisher=All India Institute of Medical Sciences, New Delhi|date=27 November 2019}}</ref>  \n| administrative_staff = 9,956<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\"/>\n| students          = 18,933<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\"/> \n| undergrad         = 3,209<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\"/> \n| postgrad          = 10,399<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\"/>\n| doctoral          = 1,991<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\"/>\n| other_students    = 3,334<ref name=\"AIIMS Annual Report\"/>\n| city              = [[New Delhi]] \n| state             = [[Delhi]]\n| country           = [ndia\n| coor              = {{Coord|28.565|77.21}}\n| campus            = Delhi\n| language          = [[English language|English]]\n| colours           =  \n| website           = {{url|https://www.aiims.edu/}} \n}}\n\n'''All India Institute of Medical Sciences, New Delhi''' ('''AIIMS New Delhi''') ([[IAST]]: ''Akhil Bh\u0101ratiya \u0100yurvignan Samsth\u0101n, Na\u012b Dill\u012b'') is a [[medical school]], [[hospital]] and [[public university|public]] [[medical research university]]  based in [[New Delhi, India]]. AIIMS (New Delhi) was established in 1956 through an Act of Parliament and operates autonomously under the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (India)|Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]].\n\n==History==\n{{anchor|All India Institute of Medical Sciences Act, 1956}}\nAIIMS (New Delhi) was established in 1956 through an Act of Parliament and operates autonomously under the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (India)|Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]].AIIMS (New Delhi) is governed by the All India Institute of Medical Sciences Act, 1956.<ref>{{cite web | authorlink = Parliament of the Republic of India | date = 2 June 1956 | url = http://www.aiims.edu/aiims/ritact/AIIMS-ACT-RULES.pdf | title = The All India Institute of Medical Sciences Act, 1956\n}}</ref> AIIMS was established in New Delhi after then Prime Minister of India [[Jawaharlal Nehru|Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru's]] initial proposal to set up the institute in Calcutta was turned down by the then Chief Minister of West Bengal [[Bidhan Chandra Roy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1050902/asp/frontpage/story_5187097.asp|title=The Telegraph - Calcutta : Frontpage|website=telegraphindia.com|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> It was the vision of [[Rajkumari Amrit Kaur]], the first Health Minister of India, to establish an institute of such nature in India.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n| type = Life Sciences and Medicine University\n| NIRF_M_2019 = 1\n| IT_M_2018 = 1\n| OUTLOOK_M_2018 = 1\n| WEEK_M_2019 = 1\n}}\n[[File:AIIMS -New Delhi's Ward Block.jpg|thumb|260x260px|'''AIIMS (New Delhi)''' Emergency block building situated within the East Campus.|alt=]]'''International Ranking:'''\n\n* AIIMS (New Delhi) was ranked '''338''' in world in 2019 in the category of Life Sciences and Medicine by [[QS World University Rankings|QS WUR]].<ref name=\"topuniversities.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/all-india-institute-medical-sciences-new-delhi/undergrad|title=All India Institute of Medical Sciences, New Delhi|date=2014-10-25|website=Top Universities|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n*AIIMS (New Delhi) was ranked '''1''' in [[South Asia]] in 2019 in the category of Life Sciences and Medicine by [[QS World University Rankings|QS WUR]].<ref name=\"topuniversities.com\"/>\n\n'''National Ranking:'''\n\n* AIIMS (New Delhi) was ranked '''1''' among all medical colleges in India by the [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] in 2019.<ref name=\"Rankings_NIRF_M_2019\" />\n* AIIMS (New Delhi) was also ranked '''1''' in India by ''[[India Today]]''<ref name=\"Rankings_IT_M_2018\" /> and ''[[Outlook India]]''<ref name=\"Rankings_OUTLOOK_M_2018\" /> in 2018 and by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]'' in 2019.<ref name=\"Rankings_WEEK_M_2019\" />\n\n== Achievements of AIIMS (New Delhi) ==\n\n* AIIMS is the first Indian center to perform a successful cardiac transplant. The surgery was performed by P Venugopal, the ex director of AIIMS in 1994.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The first successful heart transplant in India|first=P.|last=Venugopal|date=1 September 1994|journal=The National Medical Journal of India|volume=7|issue=5|pages=213\u2013215|pmid=7827600}}</ref>\n* AIIMS is an advanced center of stem cell therapy in India, especially cardiac and neurological. It holds a reputation of being a pioneer in Stem Cell Injection.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-03-23/science/27834135_1_cell-therapy-cell-study-skeletal-muscle | work=The Times of India | title=AIIMS claims cutting edge stem cell study | date=23 March 2005}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Stem cell therapy - Hope and scope in pediatric surgery|journal=Journal of Indian Association of Pediatric Surgeons|volume=10|issue=3|pages=138|doi=10.4103/0971-9261.16962|year=2005|last1=Gupta|first1=Devendrak|last2=Sharma|first2=Shilpa|url=http://www.bioline.org.br/pdf?ip05035}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-02-24/delhi/27864742_1_cell-research-cell-injection-cell-centre | work=The Times of India | first1=Vividha | last1=Kaul | title=AIIMS pioneers stem cell injection | date=24 February 2005}}</ref>\n*AIIMS has India's first and only minimally invasive surgery training center, under collaboration with Germany.<ref>[http://www.aiimslaparoscopictrainingcentre.com/introduction.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704132136/http://www.aiimslaparoscopictrainingcentre.com/introduction.htm |date=4 July 2008 }}</ref>\n*The first in-vitro fertilization facility in the public sector set up at the AIIMS (New Delhi) in February 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/02/08/stories/2008020860790300.htm/|title=Archive News - The Hindu|website=The Hindu|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n* Kayalkalp Award (Cleanest Medical Facility) for 3 consecutive years 2017, 2018 and 2019: First Prize for maintaining cleanliness within the institute's premises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/aiims-delhi-wins-top-cleanliness-award-bags-rs-3-crore/articleshow/71545703.cms|title=AIIMS Delhi wins top cleanliness award, bags Rs 3 crore {{!}} Delhi News - Times of India|last=Oct 11|first=PTI {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24|last3=Ist|first3=21:50}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/delhi-ncr/delhi-aiims-hat-trick-after-winning-kayakalp-award-for-third-time-in-a-row|title=\u0926\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u0940 \u090f\u092e\u094d\u0938 \u0915\u0940 \u0939\u0948\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u0915, \u0932\u0917\u093e\u0924\u093e\u0930 \u0924\u0940\u0938\u0930\u0940 \u092c\u093e\u0930 \u091c\u0940\u0924\u093e \u0915\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0915\u0932\u094d\u092a \u0905\u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0921|website=Amar Ujala|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n===AIIMS, New Delhi main campus===\nAIIMS New Delhi's main campus is located in Ansari Nagar in [[Delhi]]. It is adjacent to the South Extension-II market and lies on the both sides of Sir Aurobindo Marg, southwards to the AIIMS Roundabout flyover crossing.\n\nAIIMS Main campus is spread mainly into 5 locations:\n\n# '''East Campus''' - Containing OPD Block, Main Hospital Block, Ward Block, Medical College, Research Section, Convergence Block, [[Bhalchandra Babaji Dikshit|BB Dixit]] Library, Administrative Wing, Undergraduates Hostels, Central Lawn, Jawaharlal Auditorium and staff quarters. The 4 Specialty Centers for Cardiothoracic + Neurosciences, Cancer Center, Center for Ophthalmic Sciences and Center for Dental Education and Research are also within this East Campus.\n# '''West Campus -''' It comprises mainly staff quarters and residences.\n# '''JPNA Trauma Center -''' It is exclusively designated for Emergency services. In June 2018 a tunnel + ramp-road link between East campus and JPNA Trauma Center Campus was also opened. This link route is very useful in fast transferring of critical patients across the two Campuses.\n# '''Masjid Moth Campus -'''  This site contains new Post-Graduate & Resident Doctor's apartments. Underground parking block is also situated here. Upcoming New OPD Block, Mother & Child Care Unit, Surgical Block and Geriatric Block are also under construction here. These new blocks are aimed to reduce the patient load on the present OPD block in East Campus which is currently overhauled by nearly approx. 10,000 out-patients per day.\n# '''Ayurvigyan Nagar Campus -''' It is too for faculty and staff's residential accommodations.\n\n[[File:JPNA Trauma Center.jpg|thumb|JPNA Trauma Center building at '''AIIMS (New Delhi)'''|260x260px|alt=]]\n[[File:AIIMS central lawn.jpg|right|Central lawn, with teaching block in the background|thumb]]\n\nAcross AIIMS is [[Safdarjung Hospital]] and associated [[Vardhman Mahavir Medical College]] (of [[Guru Gobind Singh Indraprastha University]]). Also, adjacently lies the headquarters of [[Indian Council of Medical Research]], the body that coordinates and funds medical research in India. In vicinity, also lies [[National Medical Library]], run by the Directorate-General of Health Services of the Government of India. It has a vast collection of scientific and medical journals that can be accessed by researchers.\n\n=== Extension Campuses of AIIMS (New Delhi) ===\n\n====Jhajjar Extension campus====\n{{anchor | AIIMS (New Delhi) Jhajjar extension campus|5=National Cancer Institute|7=National Cancer Institute, Jhajjar}}\n[[File:National Cancer Institute, AIIMS (New Delhi).jpg|alt=|thumb|National Cancer Institute (NCI) at AIIMS (New Delhi)'s Jhajjar Extension campus]]\n'''AIIMS (New Delhi)'s '''Jhajjar Extension Campus was established on 24 November 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=188965|title=National Cancer Institute at Jhajjar dedicated to the nation as part of AIIMS, New Delhi|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> It spreads over 330 acres (1.335 square kilometers) of land<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-11/delhi/28055022_1_2nd-aiims-campus-site-free-land|title=Haryana offers free land for 2nd AIIMS campus|work=The Times of India|date=11 Feb 2009<!--, 02.58am IST-->|accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref> built with an initial cost of {{INRConvert|10|b}},<ref>{{cite news|title=AIIMS-II launched in Haryana village|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/health/health-news/aiims-ii-launched-in-haryana-village_17213.html|accessdate=25 May 2012 | work=The Times of India|date=25 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Work on AIIMS II project likely to begin on May 30|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-05-25/india/31851942_1_aiims-ii-aiims-ii-bhupinder-singh-hooda|accessdate=25 May 2012 | work=The Times of India|date=25 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-11-25/india/35347245_1_oopd-delhi-aiims-opd-timings | work=The Times of India | title=AIIMS begins OOPD at Jhajjar | date=25 November 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/generalnews/news/azad-inaugurates-outreach-opdaiims-in-haryana/83338/ Azad inaugurates Outreach OPD of AIIMS in Haryana]. Business Standard (24 November 2012). Retrieved on 9 October 2013.</ref>\n\n==== National Cancer Institute (NCI) and upcoming National Heart Institute ====\nThe 710 bedded National Cancer Institute of India and ''Infectious and Community Diseases Centre'' at AIIMS (New Delhi)'s Jhajjar Extension Campus is constructed at a cost of \u20b92,034 crores on 32 acres along the lines of [[National Cancer Institute]] of the USA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/AIIMS-cancer-centre-in-Jhajjar/articleshow/29428513.cms|title=AIIMS cancer centre in Jhajjar - Times of India|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> and it is focused on treatment and research on the India-specific cancer.<ref name=\"NCII1\">[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/gurgaon/inderjit-calls-on-fm-to-push-for-aiims-in-rewari/articleshow/67099633.cms Inderjit calls on FM to push for AIIMS in Rewari], Times of India, 15 Dec 2018.</ref>\n\nIt became operational on 18 December 2018 including OPD, lab and 250 bed hospital which will be expanded to 710 beds by December 2019.<ref name=\"opd1\">[https://www.amarujala.com/chandigarh/india-s-largest-cancer-hospital-national-cancer-institute-nci-haryana India's largest cancer hospital National Cancer Institute NCI at Haryana], Amarujala, Dec 2018.</ref> It is headed by Dr. G.K. Rath former Head of Department of Oncology at AIIMS (New Delhi).<ref name=\"opd1\" /> National Heart Institute (India) is also being establlished here.<ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/2012-A-story-of-Haryanas-achievements/articleshow/17697287.cms 2012: A story of Haryana's achievements], Times of India, 2012.</ref>\n\n[[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi#Jhajjar campus|IITD-Jhajjar campus]] is located next to the AIIMS (New Delhi)'s Jhajjar Extension campus. IIT-Delhi and AIIMS are to jointly set up a biomedical research park at this campus, including a joint Ph.D. supervision programme and provision for adjunct faculty. IITD-Jhajjar is funded by the IITD and managed by the ''Foundation for Innovation and Technology Transfer'' (FITT).<ref name=\"aaimsjb1\">[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/iit-delhi-aiims-to-jointly-set-up-biomedical-research-park/articleshow/65616767.cms IIT-Delhi and AIIMS to jointly set up biomedical research park ay Jhajjar], Times of India Aug 2018.</ref>\n\nA heliport is being developed here in January 2019 for the [[Air Ambulance]] to serve emergency patients from remote areas.<ref>[https://www.amarujala.com/haryana/jhajjar-bahadurgarh/51548792119-jhajjar-bahadurgarh-news Heliport at AIIMS-Badsa for air ambulance], Amar Ujala, 29 Dec 2019.</ref>\n\n====Ballabhgarh Extension campus====\nBallabhgarh, established in 1965, is an extension campus of AIIMS in [[Ballabhgarh]] city of [[Faridabad district]] in [[Haryana]].<ref name=\"bal2\">[https://www.aiims.edu/en/departments-and-centers/departments.html?id=643 AIIMS Introduction], AIIMS.</ref> This rural field practice OPD{{clarify|what does this stand for?|date=January 2018}} campus was set up in collaboration with [[Government of Haryana]] as \"Comprehensive Rural Health Services Project\" - \"Ballabgarh Health and Demographic Surveillance System\".<ref name=\"bal1\">[http://faridabad.nic.in/blb/aims.htm \"AIIMS Fridabad\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116231513/http://faridabad.nic.in/blb/aims.htm |date=16 November 2017 }}, [[National Informatics Centre]].</ref><ref name=\"bal3\">[http://www.indepth-network.org/Profiles/ballabgarh_hdss_2013.pdf \"Profile: The Ballabgarh Health and Demographic Surveillance System (CRHSP-AIIMS).\"], [http://www.indepth-network.org/ Indepth Network].</ref> In 1961 Rural Field Practice was established at AIIMS (New Delhi) with the help of [[Rockefeller Foundation]]. In 1965, the Comprehensive Rural Health Services Project was set up at Ballabgarh with a 50-bed hospital, 24 hr emergency and obstetric facilities, outpatient services in medicine, surgery, pediatrics, gynaecology & obstetrics, eye, otorhinolaryngology, psychiatry, physical medicine & rehabilitation, pediatric surgery, dental care, homeopathy, NCD{{clarify|what does this stand for?|date=January 2018}} clinic, ANC{{clarify|what does this stand for?|date=January 2018}} clinic, immunization clinic, laboratory, radiological and ultra-sonography services.<ref name=\"bal2\" /><ref name=\"bal4\">[https://www.aiims.edu/images/pdf/Departments_Centers/Centre_for_Community/Rural%20Health%20Program%20CCM.pdf AIIMS Ballabhgarh CRHS]</ref><ref name=\"bal5\">[http://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/health/healthcare-expenses-paralyse-family-finances-aiims-study/835415/ \"Healthcare expenses paralyse family finances: AIIMS study.\"], [[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]], 31 Aug 2017.</ref><ref name=\"bal6\">[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20071007/spectrum/main1.htm \"AIIMS: Ailing Institute.\"], [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]], 6 Oct 2007.</ref>\n\n====Ghaziabad Extension campus====\nAn intensive field practice area, '''NDDTC''' -National Drug Dependence Treatment Centre<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiims.edu/en/departments-and-centers/specialty-centers.html?id=414|title=National Drug Dependence Treatment Centre|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> is an extension campus of AIIMS (New Delhi) in [[Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh|Ghaziabad]] city of [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=\"bal6\" />\n\nThe Drug Dependence Treatment Centre, AIIMS was established in the year 1988 and was functional in New Delhi. In 2003 it was upgraded as a National Centre (National Drug Dependence Treatment Centre) and is fully operational from its new premises in Ghaziabad, Delhi-NCR since April 2003.\n\nNDDTC has been established as the apex centre for treatment of drugs and substance abuse disorders in the country. It provides a state of art model for de\u2010addiction treatments. This centre has full range of specialists & facilities. The NDDTC is situated on 10 acre beautiful campus. It is presently having 50 bedded treatment facilities\n\nPhD Programme in the area of Addiction Psychiatry & DM (Addiction Psychiatry) Programme started since year 2012 and 2015 respectively.\n\nThe Ex-Chief of the Centre was a member of the International Narcotics Control Board (INCB), a monitoring body under the United Nations.\n[[File:Nddtc.jpg|thumb|'''NDDTC''' of AIIMS (New Delhi)]]\nNDDTC has been designated as a WHO Collaborating Centre on Substance Abuse (2012-2020)\n\n=== AIIMS (New Delhi) Campus Redevelopment Master plan 2019 ===\nIn February 2019 The Union Cabinet chaired by Prime Minister of India has given \u2018in principle\u2019 approval to the Implementation of Master Plan to convert All India Institute of Medical Sciences (AIIMS), New Delhi into a world class Medical University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/Pressreleaseshare.aspx?PRID=1566755|title=Cabinet approves Implementation of Master Plan of AIIMS, New Delhi|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nThe visualization at the time of institute's construction ''(in 1950s)'' was for a limited number of patients. The medical institute was established as a tertiary-care centre, but now it has turned into a primary care centre. Over time, the requirement has increased manifold. The upcoming master plan will now have a vision for the next decade.\n\n* The Master Plan envisages freeing up adequate space through redevelopment, vertical expansion and reorganizing the land usage, thus optimizing the infrastructure of the Institute for the next 20 years.\n* It is proposed to re-develop the infrastructure of AIIMS, New Delhi by consolidating the Patient Care, Teaching, Research, Administration and support services in areas in the East Ansari Nagar (Main) Campus and residential facilities from East Ansari Nagar (Main Campus) to Trauma Centre Extension (New Rajnagar) Campus.\n\n'''Benefits:'''\n\nThe project would provide highly specialized state-of-the-art healthcare to the patients and an integrated \u2018One Campus\u2019 answer to all the investigative, physiotherapeutic, operative, rehabilitative and vocational needs of the patients.It would ensure smart mobility and accessibility for the patients and become an apex tertiary care centre for advancement of research, clinical applications and management of patients.\n\n==== Works expected as per the Redevelopment Master plan ====\nBy 2024, AIIMS (New Delhi) will add around 3,000 more beds to its existing strength of 2,478 beds. So there will be a facility of approximately 5,500 beds in service by then.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/under-new-master-plan-aiims-to-add-3000-beds-5616539/|title=Under new master plan, AIIMS to add 3,000 beds|date=2019-03-08|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nA move that will come as a relief for thousands of patients who visit the hospital every day as presently the hospital sees a daily footfall of almost 15,000 patients and their attendants. It also aims to strengthen patient-care services and residential facilities for faculty members and staff.\n\nOfficials said the estimated cost of executing the master plan is around \u20b910,345 crore, including \u20b91,000 crore for hiring manpower .\n\nThe project will be completed in two phases; while Phase 1 will be completed in 46 months, the second phase will be finalized in 70 months.\n\nAs per the plan, a convention centre, a guesthouse with 40 rooms, a hostel with more than 4,500 rooms and 500 residential units with allied car parking will be set up.\n\nAs There is no scope of further expansion with the limited availability of land, residential facilities stretching from Trauma Centre campus, West Campus (Ansari Nagar) to East Campus (Ansari Nagar) and Ayurvigyan Nagar Campus will be relocated. This will free up space in the main campus and allow to expand vertically.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/govt-in-principle-approves-master-plan-to-convert-aiims-into-world-class-medical-university-119022801286_1.html|title=Govt 'in principle' approves Master Plan to convert AIIMS into world class medical university|last=ANI|date=2019-02-28|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nWith senior faculty members raising issues of shortage of labs and operation theaters in the institute, the administration hopes the upcoming project will look into that concern. This new plan will also create scope for research projects, which have been pending due to space constraints.\n\n==Healthcare==\n===Medical facilities===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+'''Departments and Sub-Specialties at AIIMS (New Delhi)'''\n|\n!'''<big>Department /Sub-Specialty</big>'''\n<br />\n|-\n|1.\n|Anesthesiology\n|-\n|2.\n|Anatomy\n|-\n|3.\n|Biochemistry\n|-\n|4.\n|Biomedical Engineering\n|-\n|5.\n|Biophysics\n|-\n|6.\n|Biostatistics\n|-\n|7.\n|Biotechnology\n|-\n|8.\n|Breast and Endocrine Surgery\n|-\n|9.\n|Cardiac Anaesthesiology\n|-\n|10.\n|Cardiac Biochemistry\n|-\n|11.\n|Cardiac Pathology\n|-\n|12.\n|Cardiac Radiology\n|-\n|13.\n|Cardiology\n|-\n|14.\n|Cardio-surgical Intensive Care\n|-\n|15.\n|Cardio-thoracic & Vascular Surgery\n|-\n|16.\n|Cardio-vascular Radiology & Endovascular Interventions\n|-\n|17.\n|Community Medicine and Family Medicine\n|-\n|18.\n|Conservative Dentistry & Endodontics\n|-\n|19.\n|Dermatology and Venereology\n|-\n|20.\n|Dietetics\n|-\n|21.\n|Drug Dependence and Addiction Psychiatry\n|-\n|22.\n|Emergency Medicine\n|-\n|23.\n|Endocrinology and Metabolism\n|-\n|24.\n|Forensic Medicine and Toxicology\n|-\n|25.\n|Forensic pathology and Molecular Laboratory\n|-\n|26.\n|Gastroenterology and Human Nutrition\n|-\n|27.\n|Gastrointestinal Surgery and Liver Transplantation\n|-\n|28.\n|General Surgery and Minimal Access Surgery\n|-\n|29.\n|Geriatric Medicine\n|-\n|30.\n|Gynecological Oncology\n|-\n|31.\n|Head and Neck Surgical Oncology\n|